### Composable Type Guard Combinators

A type guard's real power isn't just returning `boolean` — it's the `x is T` return annotation that lets the compiler narrow a variable's type after the check. The challenge with combinators is that the combined guard also needs an accurate `x is ...` annotation derived from the two guards being combined, not just a generic `boolean`.

```typescript
type TypeGuard<T> = (x: unknown) => x is T;

function and<A, B>(guardA: TypeGuard<A>, guardB: TypeGuard<B>): TypeGuard<A & B> {
  return (x: unknown): x is A & B => guardA(x) && guardB(x);
}

function or<A, B>(guardA: TypeGuard<A>, guardB: TypeGuard<B>): TypeGuard<A | B> {
  return (x: unknown): x is A | B => guardA(x) || guardB(x);
}

function not<A>(guard: TypeGuard<A>): TypeGuard<Exclude<unknown, A>> {
  return (x: unknown): x is Exclude<unknown, A> => !guard(x);
}

interface HasName { name: string }
interface HasAge { age: number }

const hasName = (x: unknown): x is HasName =>
  typeof x === 'object' && x !== null && 'name' in x;
const hasAge = (x: unknown): x is HasAge =>
  typeof x === 'object' && x !== null && 'age' in x;

const isPerson = and(hasName, hasAge); // TypeGuard<HasName & HasAge>

function greet(value: unknown) {
  if (isPerson(value)) {
    console.log(value.name, value.age); // both narrowed correctly, no cast needed
  }
}
```

Each combinator's generic signature is the actual mechanism: `and` declares its return type as `TypeGuard<A & B>`, so once TypeScript sees the combined function actually used as a guard in an `if`, it applies that exact intersection to the narrowed branch — the runtime body (`guardA(x) && guardB(x)`) just has to actually agree with what the signature promises, the compiler doesn't verify the implementation matches the annotation beyond basic type checking of the body.

This composes arbitrarily deep — `and(and(hasName, hasAge), hasEmail)` correctly narrows to a three-way intersection — and the `or` combinator is what lets you build validation pipelines that narrow to clean discriminated unions instead of falling back to `unknown` after each check.

Common pitfall: writing the runtime logic and the type-level signature out of sync — for example, implementing `or` as `guardA(x) && guardB(x)` by a copy-paste mistake from `and`. Because the predicate annotation `x is A | B` is a developer-supplied promise that TypeScript trusts rather than independently verifies against the boolean logic inside, a swapped `&&`/`||` produces a guard that silently narrows incorrectly at every call site, and the bug is invisible at the type level — it only surfaces as a runtime logic error.

